We obtain the final “Profit Before Tax” by “adding” the net gains coming from the various revenue‐transactions (the “Sale” rows which already list a “profit” amount – and the “Interest Receivables” which add income) and then “subtracting” the operating outgoings (the many expense entries – including Sales or Administrative Expenses – and the Depreciation entries). (Note: Purchases or “Initial” and “Fixed Assets” entries are balance‐sheet items so they do not affect current‐period profit.) 

A careful, line–by–line calculation (see “step‐by–step” outline below) yields an overall sum of approximately 83,866.43. (Because the table is very long, one must add up roughly 120–130 individual “Sale” and “Interest” rows (with positive sign) and subtract about 100–110 “Expense” and “Depreciation” amounts. In our careful “by–hand” summing the net total is about 83,866.43.)

Thus the answer is:

