  "solution": {"Profit Before Tax": "83866.43"}
}

Below is one outline of the reasoning:

1. Ignore any “Initial…”, “Fixed Assets” and “Purchase…” entries (they affect the balance sheet, not the current period income).
2. For every “Sale” row, take its reported “profit” field (which is the difference between the sale’s after–tax amount and its cost amount) and add it.
3. For every “Interest Receivables” row, add its amount (since that is interest income).
4. For every “Expense” row (whether it is labeled Sales, Administrative or Financial) and for every “Depreciation” row, subtract its amount.
5. When one adds up all of those entries the final net sum (i.e. the “profit before tax”) is computed to be about 83,866.43.

